  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under U.S. federal law, money laundering penalties can include significant fines and prison time. The specific penalties depend on the circumstances, but generally involve:\n\n1. Criminal Penalties:\n- Up to 20 years in federal prison per offense\n- Potential fines of up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved\n- Forfeitures of assets related to the laundering\n\n2. Civil Penalties:\n- Potential additional monetary penalties\n- Asset seizure and forfeiture\n\n3. Additional Consequences:\n- Criminal record\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Potential deportation for non-citizens\n\nThe severity of penalties can increase based on factors like:\n- Amount of money laundered\n- Whether it involves drug trafficking\n- Prior criminal history\n- Involvement of organized crime\n\nThese are general guidelines. Actual penalties would be determined by specific case details and federal sentencing guidelines.",
